ultisite with XAMPP running on Windows 7\">Setting up Virtual Hosts for WordPress Multisite with XAMPP running on Windows 7</a>. Part of that tutorial was to help myself and the other was to help others. I spent quite a bit of time trying to get the newly released WordPress Mulitsite working with sub-domains, in particular <em>localhost wildcard subdomains</em>.</p>\n<p>I&#8217;ve since moved away from a windows powered machine, but the process for setting up virtual hosts for WordPress on a localhost remains about the same. You need to find where your <code>httpd-vhosts.conf</code> file is located.</p>\n<h3>Multisite Development</h3>\n<p>This was always an issue I ran into, and until today never found a solution (I also wasn&#8217;t looking that hard). But I&#8217;m in the process of moving some old sites into a network and wanted to do some local development and testing of &#8220;single site to multisite&#8221; database migration without overhead and live site breakage.</p>\n<h2>Getting Localhost Wildcard Subdomains working</h2>\n<p>As I wrote previously, or as most posts around the web pointed out, you had to add each domain as a subdomain. That&#8217;s a pain, so I usually ended up doing one or two subdomains or forcing the localhost development site as a subdirectory site.</p>\n<p>The important line is the <code>ServerAlias</code> with the current domain and then the wildward like so:</p>\n<pre>ServerAlias thefrosty.dev *.thefrosty.dev</pre>\n<p><em>Just be sure to change</em> <code>thefrosty.dev</code> <em>to your domain</em>.</p>\n<h3>The &#8220;full code&#8221;</h3>\n<p><script src=\"https://gist.github.com/thefrosty/b2461874f91823fa50b3.js\"></script></p>\n<img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/AustinPassy/~4/lD19VYQvVQo\" height=\"1\" width=\"1\" alt=\"\"/>\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:36:\"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/\";a:1:{s:10:\"commentRss\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4: